      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The mechanism is a bit intricate, but you can think of it as a series of small, energetic clashes. It starts when the reducing sugar reacts with the free amino group of an amino acid. This initial step forms a Schiff base, which is a temporary, unstable intermediate. This Schiff base then undergoes various rearrangements, often involving Amadori or Heyns rearrangements, which are key steps in the process. These rearranged products then break down further through dehydration and fragmentation, leading to the formation of melanoidins—those brown polymers that give the crust its color—and a vast array of volatile flavor compounds.",
